I may have over-reacted today when I was causally assigned yet another December task. 

There is much learned helplessness, nay, apathy wafting off my family when it comes to Christmas decor and celebration. 

I feel the tension between the brave act of letting things go and the desperate longing for the hoped for good tidings and cheer I can’t make happen.

So I’m giving up things that used to be important to me for the holidays (Christmas cards, exterior lights) because the effort to make them happen falls singularly to me. 

What’s hard to untangle, is I want those things. But not enough to lose my ever lovin mind.

I am working on NOT being triggered by critiques or casual comments from my family as to the perceived quality of their Christmas experience. Everyone is entitled to their preferences but it’s not on me to fulfill them.

I’m thinking of you as you stumble under the weight of merry making. How are you bearing of the unseen mental and physical labor of December? What would feel helpful to you right now besides a full-time Virtual Assistant?

Boundaries do not feel good to set. No one but my dear Enneagram 8’s enjoy the process of telling others ‘No’ so you can say ‘Yes’ to yourself.

But it does get easier with practice. Like any basic life skill. Plus boundaries are the way forward to staying in a long term healthy relationship.

Otherwise you end up avoiding the person or even shutting down the relationship all together. Boundaries are kind, dang it!

Let it be ok to stumble over your words and for your family member to barrel right over your limit the first few times you set one. That awkward dance is part of the process!

What boundary has someone set with you and it ended up be a very good thing even if the process sucked?

PS: This is the last week to download my Free Boundary Scripts PDF. It’s available in the link in my bio. Or comment SCRIPTS and I’ll DM you with it

Calm down with me for a moment.

A long extended exhale, combined with a shaky rendition singing or humming Silent Night. This is the soothing experience your nervous system and overworked brain are craving.

I heard someone call the collective stress you might be feeling: “holiday anxiety”. I don’t care for that phrase. Anxiety infers I am having an outsized or looping reaction to an objectively benign stressor. 

Nope. This is a simple math equation. You have more things to do than you can physically get done. That ain’t anxiety. That’s facts!

What do you still have left to do before you go to bed tonight?

Merry Christmas, sweet human! It’s ok to be sad today. It’s ok to be lonely. Those are real emotions that come and go. Be so kind to yourself.  Tell me something that theoretically makes you happy to be able to give to someone else (or yourself)!

Sibling AGGRESSION is not the same thing as sibling RIVALRY.

Rivalry is a fact of family life. It’s the natural outgrowth of siblings sharing resources (like the TV and also: Your Love!).

Sibling rivalry is competition among siblings for recognition and the attention of their parents. 

There is so much you can do to reduce rivalry. 

Sibling aggression is a form of family violence and is a sign you need to step in immediately. Unchecked repeated sibling aggression can contribute to adult mental health concerns.

The old way of dealing with sibling aggression was to train parents to reduce the negative behaviors. The new research backed way is to emphasize teaching positive social skills. 

Your role is to teach skills like self-regulation, perspective-taking, negotiation and cooperation. But what if you don’t know how?

I’ll teach you! DM me the word SIBLINGS for a link to register for my self-paced 2 hour course.

May you grow your tolerance for the giggling, crashing and screaming that is healthy consensual sibling roughhousing. 

If your past physical experiences with your own brother or sister are upsetting to think about, likely your parents didn’t provide the appropriate safety and supervision necessary to level the playing field and build the empathy necessary for both parties to feel safe and in control of their own bodies.

That’s not the present story. You are writing a gorgeous narrative where children can be sloppy and experimental and no one is left alone to figure out things with an abusive brother in the basement.

Let these present children roughhouse. Make rules together about how to end well. Help them practice caretaking when they go too far. Hold them in the space to share their big emotions and insist their sibling listen and reflect back what they are hearing. While you stay calm as a cucumber.

Supervised sibling play-fighting is a rich science lab of learning. It’s your job to ensure it is consensual and to continuously work on each child understanding how their actions affect their sibling. 

Was the sibling relationship safe when you were little? I bet you have stories.

Not sure where to draw the line or when to step in? DM me the word SIBLINGS and I’ll send you a link to register for my 2 hour self-paced course on creating peace among siblings.

My French braiding is trash. I can’t bake, clean or teach math. I get greasy take-out way more than I roast veggies. I get irritable when multiple humans try to ask for help at the same time.

But when I’m refreshed, I can hold a boundary and then listen with my whole body amidst the biggest of big feelings. 

I can delight in my child rather than try to control them. 

So can you. You are a national treasure to your child. Release yourself to do the things you are amazingly brilliant at. The things only you can do.

Only you experience that 7th sense you get that something is up when they are struggling. Only you can be their perfectly matched lifetime advocate.

Focus on your strengths. Outsource the weak parts or exchange meal prepping and organizing help with with a friend who finds you wildly creative. 

Feel no shame for hiring someone to do something you used to think was part of being a good mom.

Lovingly accept your limitations as morally neutral. Let perfection go. 

And when in doubt, mutter “good enough” to yourself.

What’s something only you can do for your child? What’s something that will have to be “good enough”?

My 18 and 16 year old children have forbidden me from sharing their likeness on Instagram. They excessively monitor whatever I post to make sure I have not breached their confidence by sharing a story from our family.

I’m committed to honoring their right to choose what goes online about them. 

And yet…
They don’t read my newsletter. 

And a girls got to have a place where she can process complex feelings in a way that might help others, right? 

If you need weekly encouragement and tips for raising a Spicy One™️, join the party. DM the word NEWS and I’ll send you a link to sign up for my newsletter in your DM’s.

What’s your policy about sharing your children’s images and stories on line?

I don’t want to brag but 3 out of 4 of us are down for the count again this year.

How does our body know that we are finally going to settle down and relax so it can get sick?? Blast you, “December let down”!

I’m currently alternating between binging Killing Eve and Circle season 5. And forcing my dog to snuggle with me.

Were you able to stay healthy this holiday? What else do I need to watch? (Of course I already finished White Lotus!)

Less than half of people who make a New Year’s resolution are successful in keeping it (when measured 6 months later).

Not great odds for losing weight or being nice to your spouse or whatever other life-changing goal you set as the clock strikes midnight.

But a single word or phrase that you share with anyone who will listen? That solidity of focus is everything!

A word or phrase that you write on a card in your car and on your bathroom mirror? That allows intention to seep into every part of your life. 

Pick a word (or for me, a POSTURE) that sums up how you want to FEEL in 2023. 
Or how you want to BE. 
Or maybe what you are CHOOSING more of this year.

Here’s my words/postures from the past:
2022: Assume Positive Intent
2021: Tender
2020: Delight
2019 Embody
2018 Magnanimous 
2017 Margin
2016 Intentional

Check out my stories later today for a recap of last year’s results (and failures) and the phrase I’m choosing this year.

Please share your word or phrase here so it can help others come up with ideas for their word.

Likely the human you chose to partner with wants good for you. They want to please you. My 2022 posture helped make my marriage a more tender place to live in.

Likely the human you chose to partner with is a beautiful soul who wants good for you. They want to please you. 

Even if years of misunderstanding and hurt have smeared your heart’s eyes to see it.

We can block the fragile gift of intimacy when we view our partner with a habitually critical and negatively-biased brain. 

Assume positive intent.

What might be different if you tried assuming your partner wants only the best for you even as they awkwardly get it wrong?

Woe to the husbands of parenting coaches out there just trying to relate to their kids without “input” from a spouse.

I’m a barrel of laughs until I’m staring at you coldly and judging you as not as evolved as me. 

In 2022, I actively nurtured the thought that:

“My husband loves me dearly and everything he does is out of a deep and abiding love for me and our family“.

Out of that exercise, I learned I don’t inherently know how to trust a partner. I trust my girlfriends but there is this block when it comes to my most sacred relationship.  So I’m practicing trusting my spouse. 

Trust is absolutely critical in intimacy.

What do you think it’s like to live with someone who doesn’t actually trust you to be a good partner?  Where are you with trust?

**edited: please note that this story is meant to shine a light on mutually reciprocal healthy relationships struggling under the weight of unchecked negativity bias.  Only you know if your relationship is abusive or if your partner is inherently untrustworthy.❤️❤️ Trust yourself!

As we wrap up the holidays, let us giggle and beam at the miracle that is your intense, passionate, independent  child.

You are an amazing parent!!

If caring well for a strong willed person is difficult for you to do with grace and calm, never fear- you are not alone.

Join my free weekly newsletter for tips and tricks for Moms of the Spicy One™️. Dm me the word “News” and I’ll send you a link to register. 

Which meme is your child?

Do you believe you can choose the way you show up as a mom?

A new client wanted her coaching goal to be: “that my spicy child will freak out less and learn to go with the flow“.

I challenged her to imagine a world where her child has three more years of freaking out like that. 

“In that world”, I asked, “how do you want to show up as a parent?”

I’m asking you the same thing.

Regardless of how your child acts, how do you want to behave as a parent?
 ⠀
That question is everything when it comes to getting cooperation and building a close relationship with your child.⠀

It will require a pause before reconnecting. To remind yourself. To choose. You can do this!

I was, er, am a dramatic and sensitive child. I am the original Spicy One™️ of which I speak!

I tell you this from experience: The leaky bucket of your child’s heart is not bottomless. Their attention and affection needs are finite. But you may need to shift a little in the way you parent. You will want to:

1. Make visible your care

2. Pursue them so 
they don’t have to always be the initiator of connection 

3. Take their feelings seriously.

Which one will you practice with your intense Spicy One™️? 

PS: I don’t personally use the word “needy” to describe myself but a family member has slung that loaded description at me on more than one occasion.

“Needy” used to sting me into retreating. Quieting. Getting smaller.

My propensity to name what I want (or what is dysfunctional in a situation) and to ask for change will always be off putting to some. Especially those that refuse to acknowledge their own needs. Or those asleep to the downward pull of drugs and alcohol

There is so much content out there, telling you what is wrong with the ADHD brain. 

The struggles. The challenges. Oh my!

Can we rest a moment in the beauty of this divergent brain. What comes easy to me, is almost impossible to my Neurotypical friends.

What superpower does your ADHD child (or maybe you) have that we can celebrate?

What tips and tricks help you navigate ADHD for you and/or your child?

Wearing shoes at home changes my whole vibe. I become All Business immediately when I hear and feel that click clack of formal footwear. 

One family uses a dry erase board in the kitchen to write a list of things they want to do or need before the ideas slip away. 

Another mom hated grocery shopping  because it was a tropical storm of distraction. Her child wanted to touch everything and buy everything. The Spicy One™️ would even pull random people’s coats to try to convince them to buy things when mom said no. Then mom started keeping the mailed flyers from the store and either circling the items needed ahead of time or letting her daughter cut them out and glue them to a blank paper. Later at the store it’s a challenge for child to find those items and bring to the cart. (You could also print out pics of your grocery list from Google images).

What helps you navigate the land of impaired executive function?

I am inviting you to practice Fierce Gratitude as the leader of your family’s culture and emotional well-being. 

They will come at you with so much negativity. So many complaints. The glass is always half full when they bring it to you.

Your role is to keep focusing folks on the good by naming it and meditating on it.

And it is an absolutely EXHAUSTING job. I see you. 

What was the last negative comment or situation that tested your positivity? Unburden yourself! Release it here and chose to keep leading your brood towards warmth and connection.

Persistent, intense and gifted children are going to ask over and over again for what they want. Their never-give-up attitude is frankly impressive.

Once you feel you have satisfactorily set a limit and been gracious enough to explain it if appropriate, STOP elaborating.

They aren’t really asking “Why?!”. They are checking the boundary. Is it really true? Is it sturdy enough to stand in the face of their upset?

When you elaborate, it can sound like pleading or even whining if you are overwhelmed. That delivery does not garner respect from the Spicy One™️.

What’s a house rule that you will commit to repeat calmly, kindly and firmly?

If you need some guidance on the whole FIRM part of gentle parenting, DM me the word FIRM and I’ll send you a link for my 1 hour class on setting boundaries with kiddos.

I remember exactly where I was and what I was doing the moment I said out-loud to another human that “I don’t like this child”. It felt dangerous like vomiting up a contagious tumor. Like the ground, in my neighborhood cul-de-sac, might open up and suck me into Hell. 

There’s nothing wrong with you if you feel sad that your child isn’t the cooperative, easy-going, positive person you hoped you would get to mother.

And there’s also nothing wrong with your intense child.

Grieving is a good and important thing. You must make space to like this child who desperately needs you (of all people) to see their unique worth and value.

Before you can like your child, you might have to first process the pain of dashed lifelong expectations for how your family was supposed to look.

Tell your story to someone safe. Admit to the deep well of sadness and anger you feel about your unfair assignment. Consider joining Moms of Spicy Ones™️, the 8 week group program that starts again in April.

The act of telling your story begins to change your story. 

Who do you trust enough to share the dark parts of parenting with? Tag that trustworthy queen below!!

There are so many ways to get to calm when overstimulation and the chaos of your family clash.

Finding what works to calm you depends on how your body’s wired and your past experiences.

May I offer Cardiac Coherence as an option?

Try to link up your heart rate to your breathing. The act of bringing your attention to the synchronicity (or the disconnection) is in itself calming.

We won’t have time to talk about this in Calm class. I have so much to teach you! Registration opens Wednesday for the LIVE January 28th on-line class that will be recorded. 

Everyone who receives my newsletters will get an invitation. If you haven’t joined the party yet, DM me the word NEWS and I’ll send you a link. 

What helps you get Calm??

You are running late and every thing your child does seems to sabotage any chance of actually getting out the door.

Rather than let the anger build as they clumsily insist on doing some ridiculous task themselves, stop and practice bilateral stimulation.

Bilateral stimulation helps you tap into the parasympathetic nervous system. Which means it calms you down.

Tap your struggling body on either side of your mid-line (think of your spine as the mid-line) in an alternating and rhythmic pattern while breathing slowly and deeply. 

Crossing the midline requires that the left and right sides of the brain work together to signal the body to use both sides at the same time. Fortunately this all over body collaboration also signals to your body that you are safe and can be calm.

Have you ever tried Bilateral Stimulation?

Your child’s body’s is running a constant threat-detection system aimed at you!

They are unconsciously assessing your body language, tone of voice, facial expressions, and more. 

Your hardened eyes tell them (outside their conscious awareness) that they are not safe.

In order for your child to cooperate or go with the flow,

they need to feel safe.

To feel safe, they need to be physically near a safe adult - one whose nervous system is in what Stephen Porges, PHD calls the “social engagement” state. 

When your nervous system is activated and chaotic, your Spicy One has no hope of remaining calm themselves.

Join me in softening your eyes! Drop a 👀
eye emoji if you accept the assignment to try this outside of a stressful moment.

You are not alone. I’ve been there. I raged at things that in hindsight seemed too small to have upset me so. 

Good news - there's nothing wrong with you. Self-regulation is a skill you learn from other calm humans. You aren’t born knowing how to get back to calm. 

You can learn how to choose calm by practicing my step by step method for responding to triggers. With modifications that honor your unique body.

You can absolutely grow your body's ability to recover from stressful inputs like your child's upset and big emotions.

Click on the link in my bio or DM me the word: CALM for your invite to Calm in the Chaos.

Are you surprised by how triggering parenting a wild child can be? How quickly you lose your cool and blow up on the little person in your house? 

I was.  I was angry a lot. But me freaking out was a similar vibe to how my mom dealt with the stress of raising 3 high energy kids. A lot of yelling in those first couple of years before I got help.

To parent differently than your parents did, you need some training. Someone outside your family system.

You aren’t supposed to know how to get to calm. Babies and children don’t know how. 

And neither do grown adults who in childhood never witnessed their trusted adult working through the steps necessary for getting to calm.

Set down your pride or your magical thinking and invest in an hour to learn the calm down recipe that works for your body.

Registration for Calm in the Chaos class is in the link in my bio. Or type CALM in my DMs if you need less to do.

What’s your parenting pet peeve that triggers the bageesus out of you?

🌶trying to finish dinner while your preschooler holds on to your leg and cries?
🌶When you defy the odds to get everyone out the door on time to school but suddenly your child has a bathroom emergency?
🌶Or when your teen borrows your new coat and now there are unexplained bleach stains on it? (That last one might be just me.)

We have things to teach and limits to set and people to love but we can’t do any of that effectively if we are raging inside. Or yelling. Or however your body responds to multiple stressors.

You can absolutely grow your body’s ability to recover from stressful inputs like your child’s upset and big emotions.

Click on the link in my bio or Dm me the word:CALM for your invite to Calm in the Chaos.

Self-regulation is a skill you can learn.

The footprint of a “good” parent has nothing to do with your child’s behavior. 

“Good parenting” has more to do with wether you have done the self-healing and education necessary to become a safe person to have big hairy feelings around.

Like Maya Angelou says: “(children) will forget what you said, (children) will forget what you did, but (children) will never forget how you made them feel.”

@jonathanldent suggested: “Imagine if we measured success by the amount of safety that (children) felt in our presence.”

Your child is wondering:
👶Can I trust you not to get angry just because I’m angry?
👶 Can I test limits without you having a tantrum?
👶 Can I make mistakes and still be worthy of your affection and positive attention?

If you struggle to stay calm when there is chaos, please know:

Take my one hour class:
Calm in the Chaos to learn 4 step by step strategies for staying calm no matter how your child behaves.

My husband thinks this impromptu song might be blasphemous. I think the good Lord is tickled by the luteal lamentations of Her image bearers who bleed.

The luteal frame of mind. It’s not relational though we crave to be understood and nurtured. And obeyed. This version of us deserves mercy. As do the people around us.

In those 5 to 7 days before your period, much of your feel good estrogen declines to an all time low. And with it goes the emotional lubrication to give people grace and see their best selves through their questionable behavior.

Some relief can come from planning. 

Planning to do takeout and frozen meals during this season. 

Planning to keep a list of your gripes, pet peeves and noticings, but wait until post-bleed to share them. 

Planning to play lazy games like “don’t wake the sleeping monster”. You lay on the ground while they run around you and every few minutes you strike out and grab someone’s foot. 

What thing about your family members kills you in the luteal phase yet you have compassion or grace for it at other points in your cycle?

A 52 year old pre-menstrual woman was made to run down a city street yesterday because her spry little niece is a real Spicy One™️. 

I see you, mom of a flight risk. 
I see you parenting with a strung out nervous system, bravely keeping your  oblivious explorer alive. It’s exhausting.

I affirm your decision to get a backpack leash or a tracking device if you think it increases the chances your Spicy One will make it to adulthood.

One day your child will check for cars at driveways and wait for you at the corner: until then, care well for your beleaguered nervous system! 

You, kind human, are a hero. 

If you need help with a plan for calming yourself down despite the numerous life and death situations you referee on the daily, register for Calm in the Chaos class.

$49. Recording included.  One week left to register.

Please send me an inhaler and some chocolates.

An Enneagram Four reviews a movie that you might be seriously underestimating:

I cried three times during Puss In Boots: The Last Wish. Tears streamed down my face while my 7 year old niece smiled at the screen with a wide toothy grin.

Cats being cute.
Dogs being ridiculously earnest.

A hilarious english cockney family of bears straight out of Peeky Blinders.

The film is deep! It delves into themes of:
🐈‍⬛toxic families 
🐈‍⬛ the isolation of celebrity 
🐈‍⬛ remembering past versions of ourselves 
🐈‍⬛ the struggle to battle anxiety while not telling anyone 
🐈‍⬛ sibling rivalry and how parents contribute
🐈‍⬛ a spicy one struggling to access gratefulness 
🐈‍⬛ cross cultural adoption wounding

Beware: It’s cartoon violent and dark (think: No Country for Old Men for elementary school kids). My 5 year old mild child would have run from the theater crying.

Will you see it?

I am sorry for what you are about to witness. 

But you need to know that over 500 people have taken the 1 hour class, Calm in the Chaos and it’s changing the trajectory of families.

Check the link in my bio or DM me the word: CALM.

Let’s get you less raging. More pausing.

Which review is your favorite?

Your family knows when you are upset or anxious without you saying a word.

Their nervous system witnesses the shift in your body language, breathing and vocalizations. 

You moving is a part of metabolizing intense feelings.

Be it the controlled destruction of ripping, shaking or stabbing…

Or dancing it out to aggressive music like “Good for You” by Olivia Rodrigo.

Allowing your body to move when it’s triggered is good parenting however goofy it may look.

Want to learn more about the steps to choosing a calm response to your triggers?

DM the word CALM to get the link to Calm in the Chaos.

How calm are you naturally? 

I’m a red hot firecracker with lava coming out of my nostrils without my Calm Down Recipe. 

Sigh. It would nice to just have a naturally grounded  nervous system but that’s not me. Thankfully we can teach ourselves how to calm down. You joining us Saturday?

When my 4-year-old would wake up her sleeping little brother, I didn’t know how to keep from yelling.  I blamed my child for the chaos and resentment swelling up in my body. 

I felt shame about my behavior afterwards.

Turns out, you aren’t supposed to know how to stay calm without someone first teaching you. Your nervous system needs to experience the calm of another’s grounded nervous system to learn how.

Don’t make yourself wrong for being a beginner when it comes to self-regulation. 

Get help with Calm in the Chaos. Live on Saturday, January 28 at 9am pst.
Registration includes access to the recording.

You are a revolutionary!!!

I’m struggling to come up with a metaphor or image to communicate how we gentle parents are out here making this lovely stuff up! We never experienced being treated with respect and tenderness when we were at our worst. Yet we attempt it anew each day.

And we mess up royally.  Then we do something our parents never considered: we reconcile. We repent. We take responsibility. 

I am so proud of you! 

If you need some mentoring on how exactly to choose calm when all you ever saw was someone loosing their mind,

DM the word CALM and I’ll drop you the link to CALM in the CHAOS

When your child is losing it, what you DO is less important than who you decide to BE. 

Work on managing your energy rather than stressing about the perfect response. 

Does it feel fake to stay calm when you feel deep emotion?

If self-regulation is a new skill for you, I’ve got you! My 1 hour Choose Calm in the Chaos Class will start you on the path to being the calmest person in the room. $49 includes recording. Live class is this Saturday!

We all have that trigger - be it blatant defiance or our kid’s whiny baby voice - that makes us uniquely more angry than makes sense. 

Swipe to see what triggers other moms of the Spicy One™️.

Hint: You can know it’s your issue when a babysitter or your sister wouldn’t bat an eye at the behavior. But for you, it unleashes a monster.

What’s the thing you find hardest to stay calm for?

If you need help finding a new way to respond, join Calm in the Chaos. Live on Saturday, January 28 at 9am pst.
Registration includes access to the recording.

Doing nothing is a great option when you are angry at your child. 

It might resemble the silent treatment while you get back to your nervous system’s baseline. That’s ok. It’s not the same thing as the passive aggressive shunning you might have endured as a child when you upset your parent.

Pausing between the offense and your reaction is half the work of becoming a safe parent.

Then you teach the lesson, correct the behavior or follow through on the limit. Once you are calm.

Heads up, ADHD people! “Magnesium deficiency afflicts 90% of all people with ADHD and triggers symptoms like restlessness, poor focus, irritability, sleep problems, and anxiety.”

- Dr. James Greenblatt in the book, Finally Focused 

And…. @psychiatry_redefined says taking ADHD stimulants may also induce nutrient depletion of Magnesium. 

So go get yourself some magnesium! Check out my MVG Favs highlight in my bio for my favorite brands.

Side note: I am pro ADHD medicine. And I’m also pro using nutrition to help make your body and mind work their best.

Do you or your kid have ADHD? What supplements do you take?

Get in here, cutie! We’re doing a February Love Challenge! 

It’s the season to start flexing those Words of Affirmation muscles to build more connection with your child.

Each day leading up to Valentine’s Day, write a beautiful truth about your child on a paper heart. Come February 14th, you can cover their door or mirror with a cornucopia of specific self-esteem building acknowledgements about their unique goodness. 

There’s a link in my highlight: MVG Favs for the heart doilies and lots of examples of how other families love bomb their people for Valentines.

What’s one aspect of your child’s character or unique way of being that you could affirm? Brag on your baby!

Find a way to put into words the unconditonal extravagant love you have for your Spicy One™️. Often.

Extra points for repeating yourself so often,  it gets memorized. 
Bonus points for a Call and Response that engages them in the affirmation.

One mom tells her complaining child, “you are a truth teller who is courageous against power.” They smile every time.

Another says to her independent defiant kid, “you are a creative problem solver”.

One mom says to her demanding and dramatic child, “you feel things deeply and help others get in touch with their emotions”.

Did your parents know to affirm you verbally? What did they say about you?

Some guidance for writing out or simply speaking acknowledgements over your Spicy One™️. 

Swipe for some ideas. Check stories for even more.

Share your first draft of an acknowledgment and I’ll help you strengthen the wording or tell you, “well done!”

I used to find my child hard to love. I come from a mother who finds me hard to love. I never met her mother but I’m betting that dynamic was there as well.

I used to wonder if it was me or my Spicy One™️ that was causing the combustion. Spoiler alert: It was me.

And now, it’s you. Not your child.  They might be a major piece of work. I don’t doubt that.

“Did you take my lipstick? 
Did. You. Take. My. Lipstick?!”

Mom’s voice is getting alarmingly louder with each repeat of the question. 

5 year old Vera is confused. Up until now, she‘s been delighted with herself. Proud of how she artfully smeared her entire mouth in thick red makeup. Just like mommy does.

“You better not lie to me. Tell me the truth. Did you take my lipstick?”

The energy is getting electric. Scary. The lightness of play is gone. Is mommy angry with me? Will she leave me all alone? 

There’s only one way to safely answer mommy’s question. Only one way to stay connected to the tribe.

“No, I didn’t take your lipstick”.

😖

When it is clear your child has disobeyed you or made a poor choice, accusatory questions rarely work as teaching tools. Aggressive questions trigger a defensive nervous system which leads to cloudy thinking. 

Which leads to lying. 

Simply state what you know: “you used my lipstick. That’s a no no. That’s mommy’s lipstick and it’s not for sharing. Let’s go clean up”.

If they insist on repeating a lie, help them get out from under the crushing weight of it by restating it as a wish.

Vera: “I used my own lipstick, not yours mommy. I promise!”
Mom: “You wish mommy’s lipstick belonged to you so you could play make-up.” Or, “You wish you were allowed to play with mom’s make-up.”

Kids 9 and under are still in the land of magical thinking. Often they can work themselves up to very much believe their own ‘lie’ which is why we treat it as a wish. 

It’s not a big deal if we don’t make it one. They will grow out of it especially if we can self-regulate and not be overly dramatic as issues arise.

Never walk a child towards a lie.

“Did you take my lipstick? 
Did. You. Take. My. Lipstick?!”

Mom’s voice is getting alarmingly louder with each repeat of the question. 

5 year old Vera is confused. Up until now, she‘s been delighted with herself. Proud of how she artfully smeared her entire mouth in thick red makeup. Just like mommy does.

“You better not lie to me. Tell me the truth. Did you take my lipstick?”

The energy is getting electric. Scary. The lightness of play is gone. Is mommy angry with me? Will she leave me all alone? 

There’s only one way to safely answer mommy’s question. Only one way to stay connected to the tribe.

“No, I didn’t take your lipstick”.

😖

When it is clear your child has disobeyed you or made a poor choice, accusatory questions rarely work as teaching tools. Aggressive questions trigger a defensive nervous system which leads to cloudy thinking. 

Which leads to lying. 

Simply state what you know: “you used my lipstick. That’s a no no. That’s mommy’s lipstick and it’s not for sharing. Let’s go clean up”.

If they insist on repeating a lie, help them get out from under the crushing weight of it by restating it as a wish.

Vera: “I used my own lipstick, not yours mommy. I promise!”
Mom: “You wish mommy’s lipstick belonged to you so you could play make-up.” Or, “You wish you were allowed to play with mom’s make-up.”

Kids 9 and under are still in the land of magical thinking. Often they can work themselves up to very much believe their own ‘lie’ which is why we treat it as a wish. 

It’s not a big deal if we don’t make it one. They will grow out of it especially if we can self-regulate and not be overly dramatic as issues arise.

Your tone of voice conveys way more than your words do. It tells your child if you like them or if they are a burden.

It’s tricky to fix our tone if we often heard a frustrated or belittling voice while growing up.

Some ideas to help you:

🎺 1. Practice with someone safe. Mimic their intonation over and over until it gets more natural. Or, record your voice in your phone and play it back when you are in a good mood. How does it feel in your belly to hear that?

🎺 2. Imagine you are talking to someone new - a potential friend. You would not dare show irritation or disdain for an adult you wanted to impress or befriend.

🎺 3. Pretend it’s someone else’s child at your house. You would work hard in that situation to stay patient and welcoming in your tone. Wouldn’t you be mortified if that child went home and said you were mean to them? Your child deserves the same tenderness!

🎺 4. Allow the Golden Rule to guide your tongue. Only speak to your child in a way you feel good about hearing out of her mouth towards you and her sibling tomorrow. Because you will hear that very same tone and words soon enough.

🎺 5. Harness the connecting power of play by imitating Bluey’s mom, Mary Poppins, Dracula or Gru (from Despicable Me) the next time you want to verbally destroy your little person.

If you are raising a teenager, you are making it up as you go. We didn’t live this life inundated with social media and adult information at such a young age. We didn’t get our first period during a pandemic or get unfettered access to porn no one should ever see.

When (not if) your teen messes up big, remember this:

1. Wait until you are calm to discuss the issue. You have time. Go in too hot and you will lose all your influence.

2. Stick to facts rather than emotions or judgment. “The neighbors Ring shows you egging their front door. Can you tell me what’s going on?” Is way more helpful than a shame soaked, “how could you?!!!”.

3. Ask them what their long term goal is. Likely they haven’t considered that yet and need your support to think broader. For example, if they tell you they hope to wait until marriage for sex, then it doesn’t make sense for them to be sneaking their ‘friend’ into the house when you’re gone. Ask them how this behavior helps or take them off track of their goals.

4. Take turns brainstorming on what they might need to do to reach their goal and how it’s likely different from a recent misbehavior of theirs.

5. Keep the conversation short! You can have multiple quick talks rather than flood your child and make them avoid you. Be transparent that that is your strategy.

6. Ask more questions and listen more than you lecture.

If you are a highly sensitive person, be that a parent, or a child, you have a a small sensory cup. 

It fills up quickly from sounds, scents, other’s emotions and tactile objects on your skin.

As the parent in charge, work to find ways to empty their sensory cup.

Believe them when they say something (like jeans!) feels yucky. If you force them to wear the offensive item, they will spend most of their body’s resources defending against it all day. That doesn’t make for a very pleasant student.

Take all the items they hate to wear and donate them to a normal kid. Ask them to pull out their 5 favorite shirts, pants, socks and so forth.

Buy duplicates.

If you are highly sensitive, what will you wear and will you refuse to wear?

Long before I learned to use words like “determined” and “passionate”, I called my 5 year old Spicy One™️ “bossy” and “defiant”. 

During one such episode 13 years ago, I was in a phase of searching for “natural consequences” rather than punishment.

After she blatantly disobeyed my rule of no climbing on the empty park stage, I insisted she ride in her toddler seat instead of her new booster as a punishment for “using up my energy”. 

I know - it’s a big old stretch.

Never mind that my “no play on stage” boundary was only meaningful to me out of fear of being judged by others. A mom in my group had made it off limits for her child. All the other children had nodded at the arbitrary rule and marched off happily to find something within parameters to play. 

Not my child. She strode up to that stage and owned it before I could drag her off.

Trying to be the adult I thought she needed, I took her hand more gently than I wanted to and we abruptly crossed the parking lot towards my car.

She began digging her fingernails into my hand. I stopped, got down to her level (like all the books say to !!) and whispered, “That hurts me. Please don’t pinch me”, my sweaty face neutral in case others were watching.

She dug her fingers deeper, throwing her head back to the sky and laughing loud and joylessly.

Refusing to backdown from my arbitrary consequence, I took a deep breath and looked at her with fake kindness and stage whispered “I won’t leave you, baby. And when you are ready you can get in the carseat and we can go.”

“I wish you would leave me. You are the most wickedest mother” she responded, her eyes sparkling perhaps with the memory of better mothers elsewhere.

That was a moment I knew my child was not like the others.

What works to help you get back to Calm?

You are running late and every thing your child does seems to sabotage any chance of actually getting out the door.

Rather than let the anger build as they clumsily insist on doing some ridiculous task themselves, stop and practice bilateral stimulation.

Bilateral stimulation helps you tap into the parasympathetic nervous system. Which means it calms you down.

Tap your struggling body on either side of your mid-line (think of your spine as the mid-line) in an alternating and rhythmic pattern while breathing slowly and deeply.

Crossing the midline requires that the left and right sides of the brain work together to signal the body to use both sides at the same time. Fortunately this all over body collaboration also signals to your body that you are safe and can be calm.
